{
  "doc_id": "12308",
  "text": "In multicellular organisms, aging involves distinctive changes in different cellular components. Cells are divided into two fundamental types: mitotic-which retain the capacity to proliferate-and postmitotic-which irreversibly lose the ability to proliferate [CITATION_1] . Because of their contrasting proliferative potential, it is conceivable that mitotic and postmitotic cells age by fundamentally different mechanisms [CITATION_2] .",
